faqItems:
  - question: "Are almond nails appropriate for the office?"
    answer: "Short to medium almond nails are appropriate for most offices. The shape itself is not the issue length is. Nails projecting 2–4mm past the fingertip read as polished and professional in the majority of workplace environments."
  - question: "Can you type with almond nails?"
    answer: "Yes, with short almond nails. The tapered sides prevent lateral catching and allow fingertip-pad contact on keys. Long almond sets require a muscle memory adjustment of one to two weeks, making them less practical for heavy keyboard users."
  - question: "Can nurses have almond nails?"
    answer: "Nurses and other healthcare workers in patient-contact roles cannot wear artificial nail extensions due to WHO hand hygiene guidelines. Short natural almond nails are the only option, and only in non-patient-contact roles."
  - question: "What length almond nails are work-appropriate?"
    answer: "A nail projection of 2–4mm past the fingertip is the professional standard. Short almond (at or just past fingertip level) is safe across virtually every industry. Medium almond (3–5mm projection) works in most standard offices. Long almond is suited to creative and fashion-forward industries only."
  - question: "What almond nail designs are best for the office?"
    answer: "Milky white, nude, soft sheer pink, and micro French tip are universally safe choices. Sheer chrome works in most offices when applied over a neutral base. Avoid 3D embellishments, rhinestones, and bold graphic art in conservative environments."
